code.name: QR
code.title: QR
code.description: QR code (abbreviated from Quick Response Code) is the trademark for a type of matrix barcode (or two-dimensional barcode) first designed in 1994 for the automotive industry in Japan. A barcode is a machine-readable optical label that contains information about the item to which it is attached. In practice, QR codes often contain data for a locator, identifier, or tracker that points to a website or application.

code.name: Pdf417
code.title: PDF 417
code.description: PDF 417 is a stacked linear barcode format used in a variety of applications such as transport, identification cards, and inventory management. "PDF" stands for Portable Data File. The "417" signifies that each pattern in the code consists of 4 bars and spaces in a pattern that is 17 units (modules) long. The PDF417 symbology was invented by Ynjiun P. Wang at Symbol Technologies in 1991. (Wang 1993) It is ISO standard 15438.

code.name: MicroPdf417
code.title: Micro Pdf417
code.description: PDF 417 is a stacked linear barcode format used in a variety of applications such as transport, identification cards, and inventory management. "PDF" stands for Portable Data File. The "417" signifies that each pattern in the code consists of 4 bars and spaces in a pattern that is 17 units (modules) long.

code.name: MacroPdf417
code.title: Macro PDF417
code.description: PDF 417 is a stacked linear barcode format used in a variety of applications such as transport, identification cards, and inventory management. "PDF" stands for Portable Data File. The "417" signifies that each pattern in the code consists of 4 bars and spaces in a pattern that is 17 units (modules) long.

code.name: DatabarExpanded
code.title: GS1 Databar Expanded
code.description: GS1 Databar Expanded. GS1 DataBar is a family of symbols most commonly seen in the GS1 DataBar Coupon.

code.name: DatabarExpandedStacked
code.title: GS1 Databar Expanded Stacked
code.description: GS1 Databar Expanded Stacked. GS1 DataBar is a family of symbols most commonly seen in the GS1 DataBar Coupon.

code.name: DatabarLimited
code.title: GS1 DataBar Expanded
code.description: GS1 DataBar is a family of symbols most commonly seen in the GS1 DataBar Coupon.

code.name: DatabarOmniDirectional
code.title: GS1 Databar OmniDirectional
code.description: GS1 Databar OmniDirectional. GS1 DataBar is a family of symbols most commonly seen in the GS1 DataBar Coupon.

code.name: DatabarStackedOmniDirectional
code.title: GS1 Databar Stacked OmniDirectional
code.description: GS1 Databar Stacked OmniDirectional. GS1 DataBar is a family of symbols most commonly seen in the GS1 DataBar Coupon.

code.name: DatabarTruncated
code.title: GS1 DataBar Truncated
code.description: GS1 DataBar is a family of symbols most commonly seen in the GS1 DataBar Coupon.

code.name: DataMatrix
code.title: Data Matrix
code.description: A Data Matrix is a two-dimensional code consisting of black and white "cells" or dots arranged in either a square or rectangular pattern, also known as a matrix. The information to be encoded can be text or numeric data.

code.name: EAN8
code.title: EAN-8
code.description: An EAN-8 is an EAN/UPC symbology barcode and is derived from the longer International Article Number (EAN-13) code.

code.name: EAN13
code.title: EAN-13
code.description: The most commonly used EAN standard is the thirteen-digit EAN-13, a superset of the original 12-digit Universal Product Code (UPC-A) standard developed in 1970 by George J. Laurer.[1] An EAN-13 number includes a 3-digit GS1 prefix (indicating country of registration or special type of product).

code.name: EAN14
code.title: EAN-14
code.description: The International Article Number (also known as European Article Number or EAN) is a standard describing a barcode symbology and numbering system used in global trade to identify a specific retail product type, in a specific packaging configuration, from a specific manufacturer. The standard has been subsumed in the Global Trade Item Number standard from the GS1 organization; the same numbers can be referred to as GTINs and can be encoded in other barcode symbologies defined by GS1. EAN barcodes are used worldwide for lookup at retail point of sale, but can also be used as numbers for other purposes such as wholesale ordering or accounting.

code.name: UPCA
code.title: UPC-A
code.description: The Universal Product Code (UPC) (redundantly: UPC code) is a barcode symbology that is widely used in the United States, Canada, Europe, Australia, New Zealand, and other countries for tracking trade items in stores. UPC (technically refers to UPC-A) consists of 12 numeric digits that are uniquely assigned to each trade item.

code.name: UPCE
code.title: UPC-E
code.description: To allow the use of UPC barcodes on smaller packages, where a full 12-digit barcode may not fit, a "zero-suppressed version of UPC was developed, called UPC-E, in which the number system digit, all trailing zeros in the manufacturer code, and all leading zeros in the product code, are suppressed (omitted).

code.name: Aztec
code.title: Aztec
code.description: Aztec Code is a type of 2D barcode invented by Andrew Longacre, Jr. and Robert Hussey in 1995.[1] The code was published by AIM, Inc. in 1997. Although the Aztec code was patented,[1] that patent was officially made public domain.[2] The aztec code is also published as ISO/IEC 24778:2008 standard. Named after the resemblance of the central finder pattern to an Aztec pyramid, Aztec code has the potential to use less space than other matrix barcodes because it does not require a surrounding blank "quiet zone".

code.name: Code128
code.title: Code 128
code.description: Code 128 is a high-density linear barcode symbology defined in ISO/IEC 15417:2007.[1] It is used for alphanumeric or numeric-only barcodes. It can encode all 128 characters of ASCII and, by use of an extension symbol (FNC4), the Latin-1 characters defined in ISO/IEC 8859-1.

code.name: GS1Code128
code.title: GS1-128
code.description: GS1-128 is an application standard of the GS1 implementation using the Code 128 barcode specification. The former correct name was UCC/EAN-128. Other no longer used names have included UCC-128 and EAN-128. The GS1-128 standard was introduced in 1989 [1] and uses a series of Application Identifiers to include additional data such as best before dates, batch numbers, quantities, weights and many other attributes needed by the user.

code.name: Code16K
code.title: Code 16K
code.description: Der Code 16K (1988) ist ein mehrreihiger Barcode und wurde von Ted Williams bei Laserlight Systems (USA) entwickelt. In den USA und in Frankreich wird der Code in der Elektronikindustrie zur Kennzeichnung von Chips und Leiterplatten benutzt. Anwendungen aus dem medizinischen Bereich in den USA sind bekannt.

code.name: Code39Extended
code.title: Code 39 Extended
code.description: Code 39 (also known as Alpha39, Code 3 of 9, Code 3/9, Type 39, USS Code 39, or USD-3) is a variable length, discrete barcode symbology. The Code 39 specification defines 43 characters, consisting of uppercase letters (A through Z), numeric digits (0 through 9) and a number of special characters (-, ., $, /, +, %, and space). An additional character (denoted "*") is used for both start and stop delimiters.

code.name: Code39Standard
code.title: Code 39 Standard
code.description: Code 39 (also known as Alpha39, Code 3 of 9, Code 3/9, Type 39, USS Code 39, or USD-3) is a variable length, discrete barcode symbology. The Code 39 specification defines 43 characters, consisting of uppercase letters (A through Z), numeric digits (0 through 9) and a number of special characters (-, ., $, /, +, %, and space). An additional character (denoted "*") is used for both start and stop delimiters.

code.name: Code93Extended
code.title: Code 93 Extended
code.description: Code 93 is a barcode symbology designed in 1982 by Intermec to provide a higher density and data security enhancement to Code 39. It is an alphanumeric, variable length symbology. Code 93 is used primarily by Canada Post to encode supplementary delivery information.

code.name: Code93Standard
code.title: Code 93 Standard
code.description: Code 93 is a barcode symbology designed in 1982 by Intermec to provide a higher density and data security enhancement to Code 39. It is an alphanumeric, variable length symbology. Code 93 is used primarily by Canada Post to encode supplementary delivery information.

code.name: OneCode
code.title: USPS OneCode
code.description: The Intelligent Mail Barcode (IM barcode) is a 65-bar barcode for use on mail in the United States.

code.name: AustraliaPost
code.title: Australia Post
code.description: Australia Post

code.name: DutchKIX
code.title: KIX-code
code.description: De KIX-code is een streepjescode die PostNL gebruikt voor het machinaal lezen van adressen. KIX staat voor Klant IndeXcode.

code.name: Postnet
code.title: Postnet
code.description: POSTNET (Postal Numeric Encoding Technique) is a barcode symbology used by the United States Postal Service to assist in directing mail. The ZIP Code or ZIP+4 code is encoded in half- and full-height bars.[1] Most often, the delivery point is added, usually being the last two digits of the address or PO box number.

code.name: RM4SCC
code.title: Royalmail (RM4SCC)
code.description: RM4SCC (Royal Mail 4-State Customer Code) is the name of the barcode character set based on the Royal Mail 4-State Bar Code symbology created by Royal Mail. The RM4SCC is used for the Royal Mail Cleanmail service. It enables UK postcodes as well as Delivery Point Suffixes (DPSs) to be easily read by a machine at high speed.

code.name: Interleaved2of5
code.title: Interleaved 2 of 5
code.description: Interleaved 2 of 5 (ITF) is a continuous two-width barcode symbology encoding digits. It is used commercially on 135 film, for ITF-14 barcodes, and on cartons of some products, while the products inside are labeled with UPC or EAN.

code.name: Standard2of5
code.title: Standard 2 of 5
code.description: Standard 2 of 5

code.name: ISBN
code.title: ISBN
code.description: The International Standard Book Number (ISBN) is a numeric commercial book identifier which is intended to be unique. Publishers purchase ISBNs from an affiliate of the International ISBN Agency.

code.name: ISMN
code.title: ISMN
code.description: The International Standard Music Number or ISMN (ISO 10957) is a thirteen-character alphanumeric identifier for printed music developed by ISO.

code.name: ISSN
code.title: ISSN
code.description: An International Standard Serial Number (ISSN) is an eight-digit serial number used to uniquely identify a serial publication, such as a magazine.[1] The ISSN is especially helpful in distinguishing between serials with the same title. ISSN are used in ordering, cataloging, interlibrary loans, and other practices in connection with serial literature.[2]

code.name: ITF14
code.title: ITF-14
code.description: ITF-14 is the GS1 implementation of an Interleaved 2 of 5 (ITF) bar code to encode a Global Trade Item Number. ITF-14 symbols are generally used on packaging levels of a product, such as a case box of 24 cans of soup. The ITF-14 will always encode 14 digits.

code.name: MaxiCode
code.title: MaxiCode
code.description: MaxiCode is a public domain, machine-readable symbol system originally created and used by United Parcel Service. Suitable for tracking and managing the shipment of packages, it resembles a barcode, but uses dots arranged in a hexagonal grid instead of bars. MaxiCode has been standardised under ISO/IEC 16023.

code.name: MSI
code.title: MSI
code.description: MSI (also known as Modified Plessey) is a barcode symbology developed by the MSI Data Corporation, based on the original Plessey Code symbology. It is a continuous symbology that is not self-checking. MSI is used primarily for inventory control, marking storage containers and shelves in warehouse environments.

code.name: Pharmacode
code.title: Pharmacode
code.description: Pharmacode, also known as Pharmaceutical Binary Code, is a barcode standard, used in the pharmaceutical industry as a packing control system. It is designed to be readable despite printing errors. It can be printed in multiple colors as a check to ensure that the remainder of the packaging (which the pharmaceutical company must print to protect itself from legal liability) is correctly printed.

code.name: SCC14
code.title: SCC-14
code.description: The Global Trade Item Number (GTIN) is an identifier for trade items, developed by GS1.[1] Such identifiers are used to look up product information in a database (often by entering the number through a barcode scanner pointed at an actual product) which may belong to a retailer, manufacturer, collector, researcher, or other entity. The uniqueness and universality of the identifier is useful in establishing which product in one database corresponds to which product in another database, especially across organizational boundaries.

code.name: SSCC18
code.title: SSCC-18
code.description: The serial shipping container code (SSCC) is an 18-digit number used to identify logistics units. In order to automate the reading process, the SSCC is often encoded in a barcode, generally GS1-128, and can also be encoded in an RFID tag. It is used in electronic commerce transactions.

code.name: PatchCode
code.title: Patch Code
code.description: Patch Code is a barcode developed by Kodak for use in automated scanning.

code.name: Codabar
code.title: Codabar
code.description: Codabar is a linear barcode symbology developed in 1972 by Pitney Bowes Corp. [1] It and its variants are also known as Codeabar, Ames Code, NW-7, Monarch, Code 2 of 7, Rationalized Codabar, ANSI/AIM BC3-1995 or USD-4.

code.name: Code11
code.title: Code 11
code.description: Code 11 is a barcode symbology developed by Intermec in 1977. It is used primarily in telecommunications. The symbol can encode any length string consisting of the digits 0–9 and the dash character (-). A twelfth code represents the start/stop character, commonly printed as "*". One or two modulo-11 check digit(s) can be included.
